<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="418" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,331,1941]" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,439,465]" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Ye &amp; Qiao &amp; Jin &amp; Bu, 2020" authorityName="Ye &amp; Qiao &amp; Jin &amp; Bu" authorityYear="2020" box="[328,489,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Perittopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anthracinus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[328,489,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">P. anthracinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[496,559,439,465]" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[496,559,439,465]" pageId="1" pageNumber="418" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
seems to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ye, Chen &amp; Bu. However" authorityName="Ye, Chen &amp; Bu. However" box="[900,1360,439,466]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Perittopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yunnanensis">
<emphasis box="[900,1066,440,465]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">P. yunnanensis</emphasis>
Ye, Chen &amp; Bu. However
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Ye &amp; Qiao &amp; Jin &amp; Bu, 2020" authorityName="Ye &amp; Qiao &amp; Jin &amp; Bu" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Perittopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anthracinus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">P. anthracinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[263,326,475,501]" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[263,326,475,501]" pageId="1" pageNumber="418" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be distinguished by these combined characteristics: antennae shining black (
<figureCitation box="[1222,1286,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1349,1373]" captionTargetBox="[164,1425,780,1314]" captionTargetId="figure-274@3.[151,1436,770,1323]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Habitus of Perittopus spp. (females). (1) P. anthracinus sp. n. (holotype); (2) P. laosensis sp. n. (holotype); (3) P. trizonus sp. n. (holotype). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539070/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); medial part of pronotum in female with a slightly blackish mark, which is absent in male (
<figureCitation box="[1010,1115,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,825,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-321@4.[151,1436,813,1913]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–13. Bodies of females (4–8) and males (9–13) of Perittopus spp. in dorsal view. (4, 9) P. anthracinus sp. n. (apterous); (5, 10) P. laosensis sp. n. (apterous); (6, 11) P. trizonus sp. n. (apterous); (7, 12) P. laosensis sp. n. (macropterous); (8, 13) P. trizonus sp. n. (macropterous). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539072/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Figs. 4, 9</figureCitation>
); mediotergites II–VI almost blackish (
<figureCitation box="[260,367,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,825,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-321@4.[151,1436,813,1913]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–13. Bodies of females (4–8) and males (9–13) of Perittopus spp. in dorsal view. (4, 9) P. anthracinus sp. n. (apterous); (5, 10) P. laosensis sp. n. (apterous); (6, 11) P. trizonus sp. n. (apterous); (7, 12) P. laosensis sp. n. (macropterous); (8, 13) P. trizonus sp. n. (macropterous). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539072/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Figs. 4, 9</figureCitation>
); mediotergites VII–VIII in female with cluster of dense long, blackish, posterodorsad-directed hairs (
<figureCitation box="[222,349,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–19" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1132,1156]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,194,1098]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[151,1436,181,1108]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 14–19. Abdomen of Perittopus spp. in dorsal and lateral view (female). (14, 17) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (15, 18) P. laosensis sp. n.; (16, 19) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539074/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 14, 17</figureCitation>
); further difference is found in the shape of paramere, which shows a relatively broad basal part and pear-shaped distally twisted part, apex slightly blunt (
<figureCitation box="[799,883,619,646]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–29" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1548,1572]" captionTargetBox="[174,1414,194,1511]" captionTargetId="figure-20@6.[151,1436,181,1524]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 20–29. Male genitalic structures of Perittopus spp.. Abdominal segment VIII in ventral views (20–22). (20) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (21) P. laosensis sp. n.; (22) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 0.1 mm. Proctigers in dorsal views (23–25). (23) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (24) P. laosensis sp. n.; (25) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 0.1 mm. Right parameres (26, 27, 29. in lateral views; 28. in perpendicular view). (26) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (27, 28) P. laosensis sp. n.; (29) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539078" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539078/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="418" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,331,1941]" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,563,655,681]" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Description of apterous female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[578,654,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1349,1373]" captionTargetBox="[164,1425,780,1314]" captionTargetId="figure-274@3.[151,1436,770,1323]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Habitus of Perittopus spp. (females). (1) P. anthracinus sp. n. (holotype); (2) P. laosensis sp. n. (holotype); (3) P. trizonus sp. n. (holotype). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539070/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[668,685,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,825,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-321@4.[151,1436,813,1913]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–13. Bodies of females (4–8) and males (9–13) of Perittopus spp. in dorsal view. (4, 9) P. anthracinus sp. n. (apterous); (5, 10) P. laosensis sp. n. (apterous); (6, 11) P. trizonus sp. n. (apterous); (7, 12) P. laosensis sp. n. (macropterous); (8, 13) P. trizonus sp. n. (macropterous). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539072/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">4</figureCitation>
). Color: ground color reddish, head reddish, labrum brownish, with buccula orange, rostrum yellowish with black apex; antennal segments I–IV shining black (
<figureCitation box="[1183,1249,691,717]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1349,1373]" captionTargetBox="[164,1425,780,1314]" captionTargetId="figure-274@3.[151,1436,770,1323]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Habitus of Perittopus spp. (females). (1) P. anthracinus sp. n. (holotype); (2) P. laosensis sp. n. (holotype); (3) P. trizonus sp. n. (holotype). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539070/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); pronotum reddish, medial part with a slightly blackish mark (
<figureCitation box="[686,754,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,825,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-321@4.[151,1436,813,1913]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–13. Bodies of females (4–8) and males (9–13) of Perittopus spp. in dorsal view. (4, 9) P. anthracinus sp. n. (apterous); (5, 10) P. laosensis sp. n. (apterous); (6, 11) P. trizonus sp. n. (apterous); (7, 12) P. laosensis sp. n. (macropterous); (8, 13) P. trizonus sp. n. (macropterous). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539072/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), area behind head along anterior margin of pronotum with a row of dark punctures, posterior part of pronotum with scattered slightly dark punctures; legs mainly blackish, basal part of femora dull orange, tibiae and tarsi black (
<figureCitation box="[717,783,799,825]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1349,1373]" captionTargetBox="[164,1425,780,1314]" captionTargetId="figure-274@3.[151,1436,770,1323]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Habitus of Perittopus spp. (females). (1) P. anthracinus sp. n. (holotype); (2) P. laosensis sp. n. (holotype); (3) P. trizonus sp. n. (holotype). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539070/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); abdominal dorsum mainly blackish except middle parts of mediotergites V–VII with dull reddish marks (
<figureCitation box="[703,773,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,825,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-321@4.[151,1436,813,1913]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–13. Bodies of females (4–8) and males (9–13) of Perittopus spp. in dorsal view. (4, 9) P. anthracinus sp. n. (apterous); (5, 10) P. laosensis sp. n. (apterous); (6, 11) P. trizonus sp. n. (apterous); (7, 12) P. laosensis sp. n. (macropterous); (8, 13) P. trizonus sp. n. (macropterous). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539072/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); abdominal venter orange. Structural characteristics: body length 3.74–3.76 (
<typeStatus box="[355,459,871,897]" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">holotype</typeStatus>
: 3.76), medium-sized, stout, bearing short, blackish, appressed pubescence and dorsum anteriorly and laterally covered by suberect and thick hairs; head deflected, head length: 0.37–0.38, head width: 0.81–0.82, about 2.16 times head length, hind margin of head laterally and ventrally with some black peg-like spiculae; antennae relatively short and stout, about 0.41 times as long as body, lengths of antennal segments I–IV: 0.40, 0.35, 0.35, 0.45; pronotum length: 1.23–1.25, pronotum width: 1.48–1.49, hind margin of pronotum broadly rounded, medially reaching basal third of mediotergite II, lateral part of pronotum medially with distinct constriction (
<figureCitation box="[212,281,1087,1113]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,825,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-321@4.[151,1436,813,1913]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–13. Bodies of females (4–8) and males (9–13) of Perittopus spp. in dorsal view. (4, 9) P. anthracinus sp. n. (apterous); (5, 10) P. laosensis sp. n. (apterous); (6, 11) P. trizonus sp. n. (apterous); (7, 12) P. laosensis sp. n. (macropterous); (8, 13) P. trizonus sp. n. (macropterous). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539072/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), posterior part distinctly wider than anterior part, mesonotum and metanotum completely hidden beneath pronotal lobe except laterally, prosternum anteromedially with one row of black peg-like spiculae; legs mainly with decumbent, suberect and blackish hairs, tarsi of fore leg short and incrassate, tarsi of middle and hind legs long and slender, lengths of leg segments (femora, tibiae, and tarsi): fore leg: 0.80, 0.71, and 0.35 (0.05 + 0.30), middle leg: 1.05, 1.14, and 0.94 (0.30 + 0.30 + 0.34), hind leg: 1.10, 1.41, and 0.67 (0.10 + 0.24 + 0.33); mediotergites not flat, areas after mediotergite IV slightly depressed, connexiva strongly raised and moderately convergent (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 14–19" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1132,1156]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,194,1098]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[151,1436,181,1108]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 14–19. Abdomen of Perittopus spp. in dorsal and lateral view (female). (14, 17) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (15, 18) P. laosensis sp. n.; (16, 19) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539074/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Figs. 14, 17</figureCitation>
); mediotergites I–III with short pubescence, mediotergites IV–VI with several long hairs, mediotergites VII–VIII with cluster of dense long, blackish, posterodorsad-directed hairs (
<figureCitation box="[897,1033,1339,1365]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–19" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1132,1156]" captionTargetBox="[163,1424,194,1098]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[151,1436,181,1108]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 14–19. Abdomen of Perittopus spp. in dorsal and lateral view (female). (14, 17) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (15, 18) P. laosensis sp. n.; (16, 19) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539074" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539074/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Figs. 14, 17</figureCitation>
), connexiva VIII with dense, blackish hairs in caudal aspect. Genital segments: gonocoxa I platelike and exposed; proctiger small, directed posteriad, with dense, short hairs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,331,1941]" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,550,1447,1473]" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Description of apterous male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[566,637,1447,1473]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,825,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-321@4.[151,1436,813,1913]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–13. Bodies of females (4–8) and males (9–13) of Perittopus spp. in dorsal view. (4, 9) P. anthracinus sp. n. (apterous); (5, 10) P. laosensis sp. n. (apterous); (6, 11) P. trizonus sp. n. (apterous); (7, 12) P. laosensis sp. n. (macropterous); (8, 13) P. trizonus sp. n. (macropterous). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539072/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Similar to female in general structure and coloration with following exceptions: body length 3.40; head length: 0.28, head width: 0.72, about 2.57 times head length, antennae about 0.44 times as long as body, lengths of antennal segments I–IV: 0.35, 0.35, 0.36, 0.45; pronotum medially with a slight constriction, pronotum length: 1.06, pronotum width: 1.26, medial part without a blackish mark (
<figureCitation box="[1235,1303,1555,1581]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,825,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-321@4.[151,1436,813,1913]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–13. Bodies of females (4–8) and males (9–13) of Perittopus spp. in dorsal view. (4, 9) P. anthracinus sp. n. (apterous); (5, 10) P. laosensis sp. n. (apterous); (6, 11) P. trizonus sp. n. (apterous); (7, 12) P. laosensis sp. n. (macropterous); (8, 13) P. trizonus sp. n. (macropterous). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539072/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); lengths of leg segments (femora, tibiae, and tarsi): fore leg: 0.84, 0.80, and 0.35 (0.05 + 0.30), middle leg: 1.05, 1.14, and 1.00 (0.30 + 0.35 + 0.35), hind leg: 1.19, 1.47, and 0.74 (0.11 + 0.28 + 0.35), grasping comb relatively long, about 0.35 times fore tibiae length; mediotergites II–VI blackish (
<figureCitation box="[768,837,1663,1689]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,825,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-321@4.[151,1436,813,1913]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–13. Bodies of females (4–8) and males (9–13) of Perittopus spp. in dorsal view. (4, 9) P. anthracinus sp. n. (apterous); (5, 10) P. laosensis sp. n. (apterous); (6, 11) P. trizonus sp. n. (apterous); (7, 12) P. laosensis sp. n. (macropterous); (8, 13) P. trizonus sp. n. (macropterous). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539072/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
), mediotergites almost flat, connexiva slightly raised and weakly convergent (
<figureCitation box="[428,497,1699,1725]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,825,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-321@4.[151,1436,813,1913]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–13. Bodies of females (4–8) and males (9–13) of Perittopus spp. in dorsal view. (4, 9) P. anthracinus sp. n. (apterous); (5, 10) P. laosensis sp. n. (apterous); (6, 11) P. trizonus sp. n. (apterous); (7, 12) P. laosensis sp. n. (macropterous); (8, 13) P. trizonus sp. n. (macropterous). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539072/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
), all mediotergites and laterotergites with sparse and long blackish hairs, mediotergites VII–VIII without cluster of dense hairs (
<figureCitation box="[661,729,1735,1761]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1937,1961]" captionTargetBox="[166,1419,825,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-321@4.[151,1436,813,1913]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–13. Bodies of females (4–8) and males (9–13) of Perittopus spp. in dorsal view. (4, 9) P. anthracinus sp. n. (apterous); (5, 10) P. laosensis sp. n. (apterous); (6, 11) P. trizonus sp. n. (apterous); (7, 12) P. laosensis sp. n. (macropterous); (8, 13) P. trizonus sp. n. (macropterous). Scale = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539072" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539072/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); abdominal segment VIII (
<figureCitation box="[1039,1120,1735,1761]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–29" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1548,1572]" captionTargetBox="[174,1414,194,1511]" captionTargetId="figure-20@6.[151,1436,181,1524]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 20–29. Male genitalic structures of Perittopus spp.. Abdominal segment VIII in ventral views (20–22). (20) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (21) P. laosensis sp. n.; (22) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 0.1 mm. Proctigers in dorsal views (23–25). (23) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (24) P. laosensis sp. n.; (25) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 0.1 mm. Right parameres (26, 27, 29. in lateral views; 28. in perpendicular view). (26) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (27, 28) P. laosensis sp. n.; (29) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539078" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539078/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
) about 1.35 times as long as wide, with dorsal hind margin concave, pygophore and proctiger simple, proctiger about 2.11 times as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[160,243,1807,1833]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–29" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1548,1572]" captionTargetBox="[174,1414,194,1511]" captionTargetId="figure-20@6.[151,1436,181,1524]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 20–29. Male genitalic structures of Perittopus spp.. Abdominal segment VIII in ventral views (20–22). (20) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (21) P. laosensis sp. n.; (22) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 0.1 mm. Proctigers in dorsal views (23–25). (23) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (24) P. laosensis sp. n.; (25) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 0.1 mm. Right parameres (26, 27, 29. in lateral views; 28. in perpendicular view). (26) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (27, 28) P. laosensis sp. n.; (29) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539078" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539078/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
), paramere with relatively broad basal part and pear-shaped distally twisted part, apex blunt (
<figureCitation box="[1286,1371,1807,1834]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–29" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1548,1572]" captionTargetBox="[174,1414,194,1511]" captionTargetId="figure-20@6.[151,1436,181,1524]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 20–29. Male genitalic structures of Perittopus spp.. Abdominal segment VIII in ventral views (20–22). (20) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (21) P. laosensis sp. n.; (22) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 0.1 mm. Proctigers in dorsal views (23–25). (23) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (24) P. laosensis sp. n.; (25) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 0.1 mm. Right parameres (26, 27, 29. in lateral views; 28. in perpendicular view). (26) P. anthracinus sp. n.; (27, 28) P. laosensis sp. n.; (29) P. trizonus sp. n.. Scale = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4539078" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4539078/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
