<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="418" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,331,1941]" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1843,1869]" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ye &amp; Qiao &amp; Jin &amp; Bu" authorityYear="2020" box="[582,716,1843,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Perittopus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="418" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anthracinus">
<emphasis box="[582,716,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="418">anthracinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” (from Latin, meaning black) refers to the nearly black color of the male and female dorsa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
